equency of 1 Hz, the cell inlet pressure is 160 mbar, with electric field parameters of 20 V and 3.11 MHz (Fig. 8 8 Single-cell capture is one of the most fundamental and widely employed techniques in single-cell manipulation. By coupling electric and fluid fields, individual cells can be trapped at designated locations, enabling downstream analysis and establishing this method as a cornerstone in single-cell research. To highlight the advantages of the device developed in this study, a comparative analysis with existing dielectrophoresis (DEP)-based cell capture technologies was conducted (see Table S11 for details). Based on the structural design of the capture sites, existing DEP-based single-cell capture methods can be classified into three main types: dielectric-assisted microtrap capture [ 34 36 40 45 46 47 31 35 36 32 39 40 This study combines finite element modeling (FEM) with experimental validation to achieve fixed-frequency capture and release of single cells within a microfluidic chip. While the device exhibits effective performance, there remains room for improving its operational efficiency and versatility. Future work will focus on several key areas to enhance device functionality. First, the uniformity of the cell suspension prior to processing is a critical factor affecting capture efficiency. Employing appropriate media to prevent cell sedimentation, as well as introducing Dean flow and secondary flow to pre-align cells before entry into the chip, are promising strategies to enhance performance. Second, optimization of electrode geometry and electric field parameters will be pursued to further improve both capture and release efficiency. Third, the device’s compatibility with various cell types will be explored. By tailoring electric field conditions, selective and precise manipulation of mixed cell populations may be achieved. Overall, the successful development of this platform provides a valuable foundation for advancing single-cell manipulation technologies. It holds considerable promise for future applications in single-cell analysis, droplet-based precision encapsulation, and cell bioprinting. Conclusions In this study, we developed a dielectrophoresis-assisted microfluidic device that enables precise single-cell capture and release at fixed frequency. A theoretical force model coupling electric and flow fields was established to guide system design and parameter optimization. FEM analysis validated the theoretical predictions and elucidated the effects of electric and flow field distributions on cell motion. Key parameters, including applied voltage ( V pp v l This work establishes a versatile and controllable platform for single-cell manipulation, with significant potential for applications in single-cell analysis, early disease diagnosis, personalized medicine, and droplet-based cell encapsulation. Future studies will focus on integrating this platform with high-throughput droplet systems to achieve scalable single-cell processing and broaden its applicability. Supplementary Information  Supplementary material 1 Supplementary material 2 Supplementary material 3 Supplementary material 4 Supplementary material 5 Supplementary material 6 Supplementary material 7 Supplementary material 8 Supplementary material 9 Supplementary material 10 Supplementary material 11 Supplementary material 12 Supplementary material 13 Supplementary material 14 Supplementary material 15 Supplementary material 16 Supplementary material 17 Publisher’s note Springer Nature remains neutral with regard to jurisdictional claims in published maps and institutional affiliations. Acknowledgements This paper was supported by the National Natural Science Foundation of China (Grant No. 32171400, 52250710157), Guangdong Basic and Applied Basic Research Foundation (Grant No. 2019B1515120037, 2022A1515220031), Hainan Province Science and Technology Special Fund (Grant No. ZDYF2022SHFZ033), and Shenzhen Science and Technology Innovation Comm